Evaluation metrics which will be used

Separation Metrics:

  • Signal-to-Distortion Ratio

  • Scale-Invariant Signal-to-Noise Ratio

  • Scale-Invariant Signal-to-Noise Ratio Improvement

Intelligibility Metrics:

  • Short-Time Objective Intelligibility (STOI)

  • Perceptual Evaluation of Speech Quality (PESQ)

Datasets which will be used:

  • WSJ0-mix
  • WHAM
  • WHAMR
  • Librimix

Probabilistic Linear Discriminant Analysis (PLDA)

Similarities with LDA

  • Able to classify data
  • Able to perform dimensionality reduction

Differences with LDA

  • Sets the problem in a probabilistic way
  • Classifies data based on probability
  • Capable of identifying new classes

Assumption:

  • Input vectors follow a Gaussian distribution

by Sergey Ioffe

Control: Avoid Obstacle

u_{i,ao} = \max \left[ -\log \left( \frac{\|\tilde{u}_{i,ao}\|}{b} \right),0 \right] \cdot \frac{\tilde{u}_{i,ao}}{\| \tilde{u}_{i,ao}}
k_{ao} \cdot u_{i,ao}

Control: Distance oneself from other Agents

\begin{aligned} u_{i,p} &= \sum_{j\in N_i} w_{ij} (x_i - x_j) \\ \frac{\partial \mathcal{E}_ij}{\partial x_i} &= w_{ij} (x_i - x_j) \end{aligned}
\begin{aligned} \mathcal{E}_{ij} &= e^{-\alpha \| x_i - x_j \|} \\ \frac{\partial \mathcal{E}_{ij}}{\partial x_{i}} &= e^{-\alpha \| x_i - x_j \|} \\ w_{ij} &= - \frac{e^{-\alpha \| x_i - x_j \|}}{e^ \| x_i - x_j \|} \end{aligned}
u_{i,p} = \sum _{j \in N_i} \underbrace{\frac{-e^{\alpha \|x_i - x_j \|}}{\| x_i - x_j \|}}_{w_{ij}} \cdot (x_i - x_j)

Control:

u_i = k_L u_{i,L} + k_p u_{i,p} + k_{ao} u_{i,ao}

       super().__init__(*args, **kwargs)

       audio = data["data"]

PCA

PLDA

In PLDA, we use a Gaussian mixture model, where \(\bm{x}\) represents a sample in the mixture, and \(\bm{y}\) represents the center of a mixture component

$$P(\bm{x}|\bm{y}) = \mathcal{N} (\bm{x}|\bm{y}, \Phi_w)$$

In LDA, for every class \(k\), we have discretized \(\mu_k\) means, and the prior of the class variable \( y \) is set to put a prob mass on each of the points

P_{LDA}(\bm{y}) = \sum_{k=1}^K \pi_k \delta(\bm{y}-\mu_k)

In PLDA, it sets so that the prior is not within a discrete set of values, but instead, sampled from a Gaussian prior

P_{PLDA}(\bm{y}) = \mathcal{N}(\bm{y}|\bm{m},\Phi_b)

Mean of whole data

Between class covariance (p.d.)

Within class cov (p.s.d.)

It should be theoretically possible to find a transformation \(V\) which can simultaneously diagonalize \(\Phi_b\) and \(\Phi_w\)

V^T \Phi_b V = \Psi
V^T \Phi_w V = I

We then define \(A = V^{-T} = \text{inv}(V^T)\), we can have

\Phi_b = A \Psi A^{T}
\Phi_w = AA^T

We then define the PLDA model as:

\begin{aligned} \boldsymbol{x} &= \boldsymbol{m} + A\boldsymbol{u} \text{ where} \\ \boldsymbol{u} &\sim \mathcal{N}(\cdot | v, I) \\ \boldsymbol{v} &\sim \mathcal{N}(\cdot | \boldsymbol{0}, \Psi) \\ \end{aligned}

We then define the PLDA model as:

\begin{aligned} \boldsymbol{x} &= \boldsymbol{m} + A\boldsymbol{u} \text{ where} \\ \boldsymbol{u} &\sim \mathcal{N}(\cdot | v, I) \\ \boldsymbol{v} &\sim \mathcal{N}(\cdot | \boldsymbol{0}, \Psi) \\ \end{aligned}
\begin{aligned} \bm{x} &= \bm{m} + A \bm{u} \\ \bm{y} &= \bm{m} + A \bm{v} \end{aligned}
\begin{aligned} \bm{u} &= V^T (\bm{x}-\bm{m}) \\ \bm{v} &= V^T (\bm{y}-\bm{m}) \end{aligned}

Learn the model parameters:     \(\bm{m}, \Psi, A \)

Learn the model parameters:     \(\textcolor{grey}{\bm{m}}, \textcolor{grey}{\Psi}, A \)

D_k = \{\bm{x}^i \: \forall i \; | \; \bm{y}^i = k, k\in K\} = \{ \bm{x}^1_k, \bm{x}^2_k, \cdots, \bm{x}^n_k \}
D = \cup D_k \quad \forall k\in K
l(\boldsymbol{x}^{1 \cdots N}) = \sum_{k=1}^K \ln P(\boldsymbol{x}^i_k : \bm{x}^i_k \in D_k) = \sum_{k=1}^K \ln P(\boldsymbol{x}^1_k, \cdots, \boldsymbol{x}^n_k)

The log likelihood for the joint distribution is set as

where the joint distribution of a set of \(n\) patterns is

\begin{aligned} P(\boldsymbol{x}^1_k, \cdots, \boldsymbol{x}^n_k) &= \int \color{red}{P(\boldsymbol{x}^1_k | \boldsymbol{y})} \cdots \color{cyan}{P(\boldsymbol{x}^n_k | \boldsymbol{y})} \color{magenta}{P(\boldsymbol{y})} d\boldsymbol{y} \\ &= \int \color{red}{\mathcal{N}(\boldsymbol{x}^1_k | \boldsymbol{y}, \Phi_w)} \cdots \color{cyan}{\mathcal{N}(\boldsymbol{x}^n_k | \boldsymbol{y}, \Phi_w)} \color{magenta}{\mathcal{N}(\boldsymbol{y} | 0, \Phi_b)} d\boldsymbol{y} \end{aligned}

Learn the model parameters:     \(\textcolor{grey}{\bm{m}}, \textcolor{grey}{\Psi}, A \)

l(\boldsymbol{x}^{1 \cdots N}) = \sum_{k=1}^K \ln P(\boldsymbol{x}^i_k : \bm{x}^i_k \in D_k) = \sum_{k=1}^K \ln P(\boldsymbol{x}^1_k, \cdots, \boldsymbol{x}^n_k)

The log likelihood for the joint distribution is set as

where the joint distribution of a set of \(n\) patterns is

\begin{aligned} P(\boldsymbol{x}^1_k, \cdots, \boldsymbol{x}^n_k) &= \int \color{red}{P(\boldsymbol{x}^1_k | \boldsymbol{y})} \cdots \color{cyan}{P(\boldsymbol{x}^n_k | \boldsymbol{y})} \color{magenta}{P(\boldsymbol{y})} d\boldsymbol{y} \\ &= \int \color{red}{\mathcal{N}(\boldsymbol{x}^1_k | \boldsymbol{y}, \Phi_w)} \cdots \color{cyan}{\mathcal{N}(\boldsymbol{x}^n_k | \boldsymbol{y}, \Phi_w)} \color{magenta}{\mathcal{N}(\boldsymbol{y} | 0, \Phi_b)} d\boldsymbol{y} \end{aligned}

By substituting the joint prob into the log likelihood, we obtain

l(\boldsymbol{x}^{1\cdots N}) = - \frac{c}{2} \left[ \ln |\Phi_b + \frac{\Phi_w}{n} | + \text{tr} \left( (\Phi_b + \frac{\Phi_w}{n})^{-1} \color{cyan}{S_b} \right) + (n-1) \ln |\Phi_w | + n \text{tr} (\Phi_w^{-1} \color{red}{S_w}) \right]

Now, we need to optimize \(l(\boldsymbol{x}^{1\cdots N})\) with respect to \(\Phi_b\) and \(\Phi_w\) subject to \(\Phi_w\) being p.d. and \(\Phi_b\) being p.s.d.

Learn the model parameters:     \(\bm{m}, \Psi, A \)

Algorithm:

Input: Training \(N\) examples from \(K\) classes, with \(n = N/K\) per class
Output: Parameters \(\boldsymbol{m}, A, \Psi\), maximizing the likelihood of the PLDA model

  1. Compute the covariance matrices \(S_b\), and \(S_w\)
  2. Compute the transformation matrix \(W\) such that \(S_b \boldsymbol{w} = \lambda S_w \boldsymbol{w}\) (i.e. \(eig(S_w^{-1}S_b)\))
  3. Compute the covariance matrices in the latent space
    • \(\Lambda_b = W^T S_b W\)
    • \(\Lambda_w = W^T S_w W\)
  4. Determine the following parameters
    • \(\boldsymbol{m} = \frac{1}{N} \sum_{i=1}^N \boldsymbol{x}_i\)
    • \(A = W^{-T} \left( \frac{n}{n-1} \Lambda_w \right)^{1/2}\)
    • \(\Psi = \max \left( 0, \frac{n-1}{n} (\Lambda_b / \Lambda_w) - \frac{1}{n} \right)\)
  5. Reduce the dimensionality to \(\hat{F}\) by keeping the largest elements of \(\Psi\), while setting the rest to zero.
  6. In the latent space \(\boldsymbol{u} = A^{-1}(\boldsymbol{x}-\boldsymbol{m})\), only the features for non-zero entries are needed for recognition

Generalized eigval problem for complex Hermitian or a real symmetric matrix

\begin{aligned} p(\boldsymbol{X}|\mu) &= \prod_{i=1}^N p(x_i|\mu) \\ &= \frac{1}{(2\pi \sigma^2)^{N/2}} \exp \left[ -\frac{1}{2\sigma^2} \sum_{i=1}^N (x_i - \mu)^2 \right] \end{aligned}
\begin{aligned} p(\mu) &\propto \exp\left[ - \frac{(\mu - \mu_0)^2}{2 \sigma_0^2} \right] \\ &\propto \mathcal{N}(\mu | \mu_0, \sigma_0^2) \end{aligned}
p(\mu \vert \boldsymbol{X}) \propto p(\boldsymbol{X} \vert \mu) p (\mu)
\begin{aligned} \mu_N &= \frac{\sigma^2}{N\sigma_0^2 + \sigma^2}\mu_0 + \frac{N\sigma_0^2}{N\sigma_0^2 + \sigma^2} \underbrace{\bar{x}}_{\mu{ML}} = \sigma_N^2 \left( \frac{\mu_0}{\sigma_0^2} + \frac{N\bar{x}}{\sigma^2} \right) \\ \sigma_N^2 &= \frac{\sigma^2\sigma_0^2}{N\sigma_0^2 + \sigma^2} \end{aligned}
\bar{x} = \mu_{ML} = N^{-1} \sum_{i=1}^N x_i
p(x|\boldsymbol{X}) = \mathcal{N} (x|\mu_N, \sigma_N^2 + \sigma^2)

Posterior Predictive Dist.

P(\boldsymbol{u}^{test} | \boldsymbol{u}_k^{train}) = \mathcal{N}\left(\boldsymbol{u}^{test} \bigg| \dfrac{\hat{\Psi}}{\hat{\Psi} + I} \boldsymbol{u}^{train}_k, I + \dfrac{\hat{\Psi}}{\hat{\Psi} + I} \right)

In order to classify \(\bm{u}^{test}\), compute \(P(\bm{u}^{test} | \bm{u}^{train}_{k}) \; \forall k \) and pick the maximum

P(\boldsymbol{v} | \boldsymbol{u}_k^{1\cdots n_k} ) = \mathcal{N}\left(\boldsymbol{v} \bigg| \dfrac{n_k \hat{\Psi}}{n_k \hat{\Psi}+I}\bar{\boldsymbol{u}}_k, \dfrac{\hat{\Psi}}{n_k \hat{\Psi}+I} \right)
\begin{aligned} P(\boldsymbol{u}^{test} &| \boldsymbol{u}_k^{train,1\cdots n_k}) = P(\boldsymbol{u}^{test} | \boldsymbol{u}_k^{train,1}, \cdots, \boldsymbol{u}_k^{train,n_k}) \\ &= \mathcal{N} \left( \boldsymbol{u}^{test} \bigg| \dfrac{n_k \hat{\Psi}}{n_k \hat{\Psi} + I} \bar{\boldsymbol{u}}^{train}_k, I + \dfrac{\hat{\Psi}}{n_k \hat{\Psi} + I} \right) \end{aligned}
\text{where }\bar{\boldsymbol{u}}_k^{train} = \frac{1}{n_k}(\boldsymbol{u}_k^{train,1} + \cdots + \boldsymbol{u}_k^{train,n_k})

Hypothesis Testing on Latent Subspace

\begin{aligned} P(\boldsymbol{u}^{test})P(\boldsymbol{u}^{train}) &= \text{likelihood of examples belonging to different classes} \\ P(\boldsymbol{u}^{test}, \boldsymbol{u}^{train}) &= \int P(\boldsymbol{u}^{test} | \boldsymbol{v}) P(\boldsymbol{u}^{train}|\boldsymbol{v}) P(\boldsymbol{v}) d\boldsymbol{v} \\ &= \text{likelihood of examples belonging to the same class} \end{aligned}

To determine whether two samples belong to the same class or not, we can compute the following likelihoods

A generalized formulation, where there are multiple examples, the likelihood ratio is set as

\begin{aligned} R({\boldsymbol{u}^{1\cdots m}_{train}},{\boldsymbol{u}^{1\cdots n}_{test}}) &= \frac{\text{likelihood(same)}}{\text{likelihood(diff)}} = \frac{P(\boldsymbol{u}^{1\cdots m}_{train},\boldsymbol{u}^{1\cdots n}_{test})}{P(\boldsymbol{u}^{1\cdots m}_{test})P(\boldsymbol{u}^{1\cdots n}_{train})} \\ P(\boldsymbol{u}^{1\cdots n}) = P(\boldsymbol{u}^1, \boldsymbol{u}^2, \cdots, \boldsymbol{u}^n) &= \int P(\boldsymbol{u}^1 | \boldsymbol{v}) \cdots P(\boldsymbol{u}^n|\boldsymbol{v}) P(\boldsymbol{v}) d\boldsymbol{v} \\ &= \prod_{t=1}^d \frac{1}{\sqrt{(2\pi)^n (\psi_t + \frac{1}{n})}} \exp \left( - \frac{\bar{u}_t^2}{2(\psi_t + \frac{1}{n})} - \frac{\sum{i=1}^n (u_t^i - \bar{u}_t)^2}{2} \right) \end{aligned}
\text{where } \bar{u}_t = \frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n u_t^i

Hypothesis Testing on Latent Subspace

A generalized formulation, where there are multiple examples, the likelihood ratio is set as

\begin{aligned} R({\boldsymbol{u}^{1\cdots m}_{train}},{\boldsymbol{u}^{1\cdots n}_{test}}) &= \frac{\text{likelihood(same)}}{\text{likelihood(diff)}} = \frac{P(\boldsymbol{u}^{1\cdots m}_{train},\boldsymbol{u}^{1\cdots n}_{test})}{P(\boldsymbol{u}^{1\cdots m}_{test})P(\boldsymbol{u}^{1\cdots n}_{train})} \\ P(\boldsymbol{u}^{1\cdots n}) = P(\boldsymbol{u}^1, \boldsymbol{u}^2, \cdots, \boldsymbol{u}^n) &= \int P(\boldsymbol{u}^1 | \boldsymbol{v}) \cdots P(\boldsymbol{u}^n|\boldsymbol{v}) P(\boldsymbol{v}) d\boldsymbol{v} \\ &= \prod_{t=1}^d \frac{1}{\sqrt{(2\pi)^n (\psi_t + \frac{1}{n})}} \exp \left( - \frac{\bar{u}t^2}{2(\psi_t + \frac{1}{n})} - \frac{\sum{i=1}^n (u_t^i - \bar{u}_t)^2}{2} \right) \end{aligned}
\text{where } \bar{u}_t = \frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n u_t^i

By using the marginal likelihoods, we can start to compute each of the different case scenarios

\log[P(\boldsymbol{u}^1,\cdots,\boldsymbol{u}^{n})] = \sum_{f=1}^{\hat{F}} -\frac{n}{2} \log(2\pi) - \frac{1}{2} \log(n \Sigma^{prior} + I) -\frac{\sum{\boldsymbol{u} \in U_{model}} \boldsymbol{u}}{2} + \frac{n^2 \Sigma^{prior} \bar{\boldsymbol{u}}^2}{2(n\Sigma^{prior} + I)}

Hypothesis Testing on Latent Subspace

By using the marginal likelihoods, we can start to compute each of the different case scenarios

\log[P(\boldsymbol{u}^1,\cdots,\boldsymbol{u}^{n})] = \sum_{f=1}^{\hat{F}} -\frac{n}{2} \log(2\pi) - \frac{1}{2} \log(n \Sigma^{prior} + I) -\frac{\sum{\boldsymbol{u} \in U_{model}} \boldsymbol{u}}{2} + \frac{n^2 \Sigma^{prior} \bar{\boldsymbol{u}}^2}{2(n\Sigma^{prior} + I)}

We can then compute the following

\begin{aligned} \log[P(\boldsymbol{u}_{test}^{1\cdots m})] &= \text{log likelihood for test set} \\ \log[P(\boldsymbol{u}_{train}^{1\cdots n})] &= \text{log likelihood for train set} \\ \log[P(\boldsymbol{u}_{train,test}^{1\cdots m+n})] &= \text{log likelihood for combined set} \end{aligned}

We can then compute the log ratio between them

\log(R) = \log[P(\boldsymbol{u}_{train,test}^{1\cdots m+n})] - [\log(P(\boldsymbol{u}_{test}^{1\cdots m}) + \log(P(\boldsymbol{u}_{train}^{1\cdots n})]
\begin{aligned} \log(R) < 0 \quad &\rightarrow \quad \text{Belong to different classes} \\ \log(R) > 0 \quad &\rightarrow \quad \text{Belong to the same class} \end{aligned}
